  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3963276053" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3963276053" />
    <a title="George Russell" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/107916505-george-russell"><img alt="George Russell" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1604090768p2/107916505.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3963276053?book_show_action=true">May 19, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="George Russell" class="user" itemprop="url" name="George Russell" href="/user/show/107916505-george-russell">George Russell</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3963276053" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3515634656790547844">Ana Castillo sets her tale of a mother and four daughters in New Mexico. Curiously, the mother and the two older daughters are more involved with contemporary times, the younger two with the area’s traditions. Sofia becomes the first woman mayor of her town, Esperanza is serving a stint as a journalist in the Middle East, and Fe works in a chemical factory. Caridad is a clairvoyant, and La Loca, who died and came back to life at age three, is viewed as a kind of mad saint.<br/><br/>Though Castillo has wri</span>
  <span id="freeText3515634656790547844" style="display:none">Ana Castillo sets her tale of a mother and four daughters in New Mexico. Curiously, the mother and the two older daughters are more involved with contemporary times, the younger two with the area’s traditions. Sofia becomes the first woman mayor of her town, Esperanza is serving a stint as a journalist in the Middle East, and Fe works in a chemical factory. Caridad is a clairvoyant, and La Loca, who died and came back to life at age three, is viewed as a kind of mad saint.<br /><br />Though Castillo has written the novel in English, she seeks to place her New Mexico tale in a tradition of international Spanish literature and Latin American culture. The title comes from a remark by Porfirio Diaz about Mexico. As Miguel Cervantes did with Don Quixote, she heads her chapters with descriptors. The family story perhaps shows the influence of Sandra Cisneros. As with Gabriel Garcia Márquez, her story takes place in an obscure small town with an oral history that tends toward the fanciful. Some cultural items she mentions are traditional cures, penitents, La Llorona, and psychic surgery.<br /><br />What perplexes me, however, is how Castillo wants us to view the narrator. The narration is mostly in informal language, with occasional Spanish words, but does not always give the sense of someone speaking. For example, on page 25,<br /><br />“Epilepsy notwithstanding, there was much left unexplained and for this reason Sofi’s baby grew up at home, away from strangers who might be witnesses to her astonishing behavior, and she eventually earned the name around the Rio Abajo region and beyond, of La Loca Santa.”<br /><br />If I try to hear the passage in my mind as someone speaking, I can hear only someone reading aloud. On the other hand, the narrative voice often uses negative concord, as on p. 45: “Caridad insisted on finding her own place without asking no one, …” Such usage is more characteristic of spoken language, and, moreover, it suggests a personality. I found one more such suggestion within the heading of Chapter 15: “a Few Random Political Remarks by the Highly Opinionated Narrator.” But by the end of the book, I still did not know who the narrator was meant to me.<br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3515634656790547844" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


